Allied Irish, Aviva, BP Plc: U.K., Irish Equity Market Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t
-- 
2011-04-15T00:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-14/allied-irish-aviva-bp-plc-u-k-irish-equity-market-preview.html
The following is a list of
companies that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and
Irish markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last market close.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index (UKX)  dropped 46.64 points, or 0.8
percent, to 5,963.80. The  FTSE All-Share Index (ASX)  fell 0.7 percent
while Ireland’s ISEQ Index advanced less than 0.1 percent.  Allied Irish Banks Plc (ALBK)  : Irish Finance Minister
 Michael Noonan  expects subordinated bondholders of the Dublin-
based, government controlled lender to take a discount of about
80 percent, he said in an interview with RTE television. The
shares were unchanged at 0.24 euros.  Aviva Plc (AV/)  : The U.K.’s second biggest insurer by
market value named Joseph Wittrock to manage its U.S. portfolio
valued at about $50 billion. The shares retreated 1.6 percent to
436.2 pence.  BP Plc (BP/ LN): The oil producer faced down shareholder
protests at its first annual meeting since last year’s  Gulf of
Mexico  oil spill that left 11 workers dead and exposed the
company to billions of dollars in fines and clean-up costs.  Separately, James Dupree,  BP Plc (BP/) ’s regional president for
the Gulf of Mexico said the London-based company will improve
the equipment used to prevent wells from blowing out in deep-
water drilling. The shares dropped 0.9 percent to 460.05 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blanche Gatt in London at 
 bgatt@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Colin Keatinge at 
 ckeatinge@bloomberg.net . 